
JIRA-001 — Patch critical RCE vulnerability on Azure VM and App Service
JIRA-002 — Remediate critical Azure Storage Account vulnerability
JIRA-003 — Fix Java deserialization vulnerability via Commons Collections upgrade
JIRA-004 — Upgrade curl/libcurl to resolve heap buffer overflow (CVE-2023-38545)
JIRA-005 — Patch Apache Hadoop arbitrary file upload vulnerability

Description
A critical remote code execution vulnerability (CVE-2025-55315) has been identified affecting 32 Azure VM and App Service resources. Exploitation could allow unauthenticated attackers to execute arbitrary code, compromising the OS and runtime environment. Exposed credentials must be rotated as part of remediation to prevent lateral movement.

Acceptance criteria
OS and runtime patched to the vendor-recommended version on all 32 affected resources
Vendor security advisory applied and confirmed on each instance
All credentials exposed during the vulnerability window have been rotated
Wiz rescan returns no findings for CVE-2025-55315 on affected resources
No new critical alerts triggered within 48 hours of patch deployment

Description
CVE-2025-15467 is a critical vulnerability affecting 25 Azure Storage Account resources. The flaw may allow unauthorized access or data exfiltration due to misconfigured or unpatched storage firewall rules. Immediate hardening of firewall rules, application of the Microsoft patch, and enabling advanced threat protection is required.

Acceptance criteria
Storage account firewall rules updated to restrict access to approved IP ranges and VNets only
Microsoft security patch applied to all 25 affected storage accounts
Advanced threat protection (Microsoft Defender for Storage) enabled on all affected resources
Wiz rescan confirms CVE-2025-15467 is resolved across all impacted accounts
No unauthorized access events logged post-remediation

Description
CVE-2015-7501 is a well-known high-severity Java deserialization vulnerability in the Apache Commons Collections library affecting 12 resources. Exploitation allows remote code execution through crafted deserialization payloads. The fix requires upgrading the library to a patched version, removing unsafe deserialization patterns, and applying input validation.

Acceptance criteria
Apache Commons Collections library upgraded to a patched version (≥3.2.2 or ≥4.1) on all 12 affected services
All instances of unsafe Java deserialization removed from the codebase
Input validation enforced on all deserialization entry points
Static code analysis confirms no remaining gadget chain vulnerabilities
Wiz rescan returns no findings for CVE-2015-7501

Description
CVE-2023-38545 is a medium-severity heap buffer overflow vulnerability in curl and libcurl affecting 7 resources. The flaw can be triggered via a malicious SOCKS5 proxy response. Remediation requires upgrading curl to version 8.4.0 or later and auditing all curl usage in the codebase to remove insecure patterns.

Acceptance criteria
curl and libcurl upgraded to version ≥ 8.4.0 on all 7 affected resources
All curl usage in the codebase reviewed and insecure patterns resolved
No SOCKS5 proxy configurations left in an exploitable state
Wiz rescan confirms CVE-2023-38545 is no longer present on affected resources

Description
CVE-2022-26612 is a medium-severity vulnerability in Apache Hadoop affecting 7 resources. The flaw allows malicious actors to upload arbitrary files via the HTTP server, potentially leading to remote code execution or data compromise. Remediation requires upgrading Hadoop to the patched version and restricting file upload permissions.

Acceptance criteria
Apache Hadoop upgraded to the patched version on all 7 affected resources
File upload permissions restricted to authorised roles and processes only
Hadoop HTTP server endpoints audited and unnecessary upload endpoints disabled
Wiz rescan confirms CVE-2022-26612 is resolved on all affected resources
